SIMPLE: tunnel
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tunnel
<hw>Tun"nel</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧n"n⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>tonnelle</ets> a semicircular, wagon-headed vault, a tunnel net, an
arbor, OF. also <ets>tonnel</ets>; dim. of <ets>tonne</ets> a tun; -- so
named from its resemblance to a tun in shape. See <er>Ton</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A vessel with a broad mouth at one end, and a pipe or
tube at the other, for conveying liquor, fluids, etc., into casks,
bottles, or other vessels; a funnel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The opening of a chimney for the passage of smoke; a
flue; a funnel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And one great chimney, whose long <qex>tunnel</qex> thence⟦br⟧
The smoke forth threw.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An artificial passage or archway for conducting
canals, roads, or railroads under elevated ground, for the formation of
roads under rivers or canals, and the construction of sewers, drains,
and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A level passage driven across
the measures, or at right angles to veins which it is desired to reach;
-- distinguished from the <contr>drift</contr>, or
<contr>gangway</contr>, which is led along the vein when reached by the
tunnel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tunnel head</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>the top of
a smelting furnace where the materials are put in.</cd> --
<col><b>Tunnel kiln</b></col>, <cd>a limekiln in which coal is burned,
as distinguished from a <contr>flame kiln</contr>, in which wood or peat
is used.</cd> -- <col><b>Tunnel net</b></col>, <cd>a net with a wide
mouth at one end and narrow at the other.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Tunnel
pit</b></col>, <col><b>Tunnel shaft</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a pit or shaft
sunk from the top of the ground to the level of a tunnel, for drawing up
the earth and stones, for ventilation, lighting, and the
like.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tunnel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tunnel
<hw>Tun"nel</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tunneled</conjf> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧n"n⟦ecr⟧ld)</pr> or
<conjf>Tunnelled</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tunneling</conjf> or <conjf>Tunnelling</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To form into a tunnel, or funnel, or to form like a
tunnel; <as>as, to <ex>tunnel</ex> fibrous plants into nests</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Derham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To catch in a tunnel net.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make an opening, or a passageway, through or
under; <as>as, to <ex>tunnel</ex> a mountain; to <ex>tunnel</ex> a
river.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tunnel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tunnel
<hw>Tun"nel</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a tunnel; <as>as, to
<ex>tunnel</ex> under a river</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tunnel stern</ent>⟦br⟧
